<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="90" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1779,2020]" pageId="9" pageNumber="90">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1851,1876]" pageId="9" pageNumber="90">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[336,494,1851,1876]" class="Anthozoa" family="Chrysogorgiidae" genus="Chrysogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="9" pageNumber="90" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[336,494,1851,1876]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="90">Chrysogorgia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with uniplanar wiry colonies, slightly flexible at terminal branches, sparse and straight branches and strongly dichotomous branching pattern. Polyps cylindrical, sparsely distributed only on convex face of the colony, perpendicularly or slightly inclined upwards. Body wall of zooids filled with tuberculated spindles, longitudinally arranged. Coenenchymal scales with serrated margins, sometimes with a median waist and with small and low tubercles. Tentacular scales irregular with serrated margins.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="91" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,350,151,176]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">Description:</emphasis>
Colony uniplanar, slightly convex, 
<quantity box="[784,859,152,176]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" unit="cm" value="14.0">14 cm</quantity>
maximum height, with sparse straight branches curved on the polypar face. Branching pattern strongly dichotomous (
<figureCitation box="[943,1011,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1864,1886]" captionTargetBox="[292,1294,265,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[292,1295,265,1840]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Deep-water Chrysogorgiidae from Brazil. A: holotype of Chrysogorgia upsilonia sp. nov. (MNRJ 6016); B: holotype of Chrysogorgia tuberculata sp. nov. (MNRJ 8565); C: Chrysogorgia multiflora Deichmann, 1936 (MOUFPE-CNI 147); D: Paratype of Chrysogorgia upsilonia (MNRJ 6016); E: juvenile colony of Chrysogorgia fewkesi Verrill, 1883 (MNRJ 6703); F: adult colony of C. fewkesi (MOUFPE-CNI 148); G: Chrysogorgia elegans (MNRJ 6785); H: holotype of Radicipes kopelatos sp. nov. (MNRJ 8566). Scale bars: 10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241600/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">
Fig. 
<number box="[996,1011,188,212]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A,D). Axis with smooth texture, base broken (lost). Uniform diameter in main stem (
<quantity box="[728,826,224,248]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="1.9">1.9 mm</quantity>
). Diameter of secondary branches decreases every bifurcation; thickness of last branches typically 
<quantity box="[718,811,260,284]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.1 mm</quantity>
. Branches up to tenth order, most commonly fifth to eighth. First bifurcations with angles 
<number box="[605,635,295,320]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="65.0">65</number>
°– 
<number box="[661,693,295,320]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="70.0">70</number>
°; last bifurcations angles 
<number box="[1007,1038,295,320]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="30.0">30</number>
°– 
<number box="[1064,1095,295,320]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="45.0">45</number>
°. Main stem 
<quantity box="[1259,1366,295,320]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.68" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="16.8">16.8 mm</quantity>
long. Branches 
<quantity box="[265,374,332,356]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="0.4" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="17.0" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="4.0">4–30 mm</quantity>
long, regardless of order. Polyps cylindrical polyps, to 4.0 mm long, 
<quantity box="[1178,1265,332,356]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.3 mm</quantity>
diameter (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1660,1682]" captionTargetBox="[405,1181,195,1637]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[405,1182,195,1637]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6. Sclerites of Chrysogorgia upsilonia sp. nov. (MNRJ 6016). A: polyp view; B: spindles from body wall; C: coenenchymal scales; D: tentacular scales. Scale bars: A: 1.0 mm; B: 0.05 mm; C – D: 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241604/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,166,367,392]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
A), sparsely distributed only on convex face, perpendicularly or slightly inclined upwards. Body wall of zooids filled with tuberculate spindles, longitudinally arranged, 
<quantity box="[820,989,404,429]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" metricValueMax="6.7" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="0.46" valueMax="0.67" valueMin="0.25">0.25–0.67 mm</quantity>
long (
<figureCitation box="[1068,1140,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1660,1682]" captionTargetBox="[405,1181,195,1637]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[405,1182,195,1637]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6. Sclerites of Chrysogorgia upsilonia sp. nov. (MNRJ 6016). A: polyp view; B: spindles from body wall; C: coenenchymal scales; D: tentacular scales. Scale bars: A: 1.0 mm; B: 0.05 mm; C – D: 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241604/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">
Fig. 
<number box="[1125,1140,404,429]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
A,B, 
<number box="[1203,1218,404,428]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="7.0">7</number>
A). Coenenchymal scales with serrate margins, sometimes waisted and with small, low tubercles, 
<quantity box="[1044,1210,440,464]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.05" metricValueMax="3.3" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="0.205" valueMax="0.33" valueMin="0.08">0.08–0.33 mm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="0.055" valueMax="0.08" valueMin="0.03">0.03–0.08 mm</quantity>
wide (
<figureCitation box="[273,341,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1660,1682]" captionTargetBox="[405,1181,195,1637]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[405,1182,195,1637]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6. Sclerites of Chrysogorgia upsilonia sp. nov. (MNRJ 6016). A: polyp view; B: spindles from body wall; C: coenenchymal scales; D: tentacular scales. Scale bars: A: 1.0 mm; B: 0.05 mm; C – D: 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241604/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">
Fig. 
<number box="[326,341,476,501]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
C, 
<number box="[374,390,476,500]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="7.0">7</number>
B). Tentacular scales irregular, with serrate margins, 
<quantity box="[993,1158,476,501]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="0.6" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="0.11" valueMax="0.16" valueMin="0.06">0.06–0.16 mm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity box="[1271,1436,476,500]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="0.03" valueMax="0.04" valueMin="0.02">0.02–0.04 mm</quantity>
wide (
<figureCitation box="[222,291,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1660,1682]" captionTargetBox="[405,1181,195,1637]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[405,1182,195,1637]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6. Sclerites of Chrysogorgia upsilonia sp. nov. (MNRJ 6016). A: polyp view; B: spindles from body wall; C: coenenchymal scales; D: tentacular scales. Scale bars: A: 1.0 mm; B: 0.05 mm; C – D: 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241604/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">
Fig. 
<number box="[276,291,511,536]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
D, 
<number box="[326,341,512,536]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="7.0">7</number>
C).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,495,548,573]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">
Variability of 
<typeStatus box="[376,490,548,573]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">paratype</typeStatus>
:
</emphasis>
A striking feature of the 
<typeStatus box="[807,906,549,573]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">paratype</typeStatus>
is the extremely short (
<quantity box="[1196,1268,548,572]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
) second-order branch. Another difference is the number of remaining polyps in each colony, which is due to damage caused by collection method. There is little variation between the sclerites of the 
<typeStatus box="[962,1062,620,645]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">holotype</typeStatus>
and those of 
<typeStatus box="[1217,1320,621,645]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">paratype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="93" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,655,680]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">Remarks:</emphasis>
Although incomplete (lacking holdfast) (
<figureCitation box="[809,881,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1864,1886]" captionTargetBox="[292,1294,265,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[292,1295,265,1840]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Deep-water Chrysogorgiidae from Brazil. A: holotype of Chrysogorgia upsilonia sp. nov. (MNRJ 6016); B: holotype of Chrysogorgia tuberculata sp. nov. (MNRJ 8565); C: Chrysogorgia multiflora Deichmann, 1936 (MOUFPE-CNI 147); D: Paratype of Chrysogorgia upsilonia (MNRJ 6016); E: juvenile colony of Chrysogorgia fewkesi Verrill, 1883 (MNRJ 6703); F: adult colony of C. fewkesi (MOUFPE-CNI 148); G: Chrysogorgia elegans (MNRJ 6785); H: holotype of Radicipes kopelatos sp. nov. (MNRJ 8566). Scale bars: 10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241600/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">
Fig. 
<number box="[866,881,656,680]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A,D), it seems to us that the specimens had its main stems broken near the basis, as typically occurs in chrysogorgiids attached to hard substrates that were collected by trawling (
<figureCitation box="[417,483,727,752]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1997,2019]" captionTargetBox="[186,1417,216,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,195,1972]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Map of collection stations of Chrysogorgiidae in Brazil." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241599/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="91">
Fig. 
<number box="[473,483,728,752]" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
C,E,F,G). Therefore, here we describe the species with a dichotomous branching pattern; nevertheless this interpretation would change if new specimens show a different pattern.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241603/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="91" targetBox="[174,1412,841,1831]" targetPageId="10">
